# Documentation and Open Questions

## Applies when

Apply when creating, reviewing, or modifying PRD files, Cursor rules, README/changelog/docs, implementation notes, static scans for docs, open questions, accepted fixes, cross-document references, or tests that enforce documentation/source-of-truth rules. Priority: High.

## Source of truth

- `docs/prd/00_INDEX.md` owns the PRD map, reading order, cross-document reference format, and documentation update rules.
- `docs/prd/21_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FIXES.md` owns `OQ-*` and `FIX-*` tracking, required fields, statuses, ambiguity handling, and static scan expectations.
- Owner PRD files own final executable requirements for their domains.

This rule is a guardrail summary for documentation and open questions. It must not override owner PRDs, `00_INDEX.md`, or `21_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FIXES.md`. If a documentation edit would change implementation behavior, update the owner PRD and tests before implementing code.

## Single owner rule

- Every requirement must have exactly one owner PRD module.
- Update only the file that owns the rule.
- Do not create a second source of truth in Cursor rules, README, changelog, implementation notes, comments, tests, roadmap, skills, or generated docs.
- Cursor rules may summarize guardrails, but must not become independent balance, schema, API, event, or behavior authority.
- Roadmap, skills, comments, and future code are not sources of truth when they conflict with owner PRDs or accepted `FIX-*`.

## Cross-references

- Use cross-references instead of copying full tables, formulas, schemas, payloads, card lists, balance values, or long rule descriptions.
- If a rule must be mentioned in another file, link to the owner source file.
- Use the documented format:

```text
See: 05_CARDS_DATABASE.md#war-cards
See: 07_COMBAT_SYSTEM.md#defense-resolution
See: 14_DETERMINISTIC_RANDOM.md#replay-test
```

- If a change affects other systems, add a cross-reference to the affected owner module.
- If a rule changes, update the owner file and keep references pointing to it.

## Open questions

- Use `OQ-*` only for unresolved missing behavior, ambiguity, ownership uncertainty, or contradiction.
- Every open question must use stable IDs like `OQ-001`; do not reuse deleted IDs.
- Every `OQ-*` must identify one owner module. If ownership is unclear, resolve ownership first.
- Do not hide unresolved ambiguity inside code comments, tests, TODOs, implementation notes, or Cursor rules.
- Do not implement unresolved behavior.
- If an existing `OQ-*` is open, follow its blocking rule.
- If an existing `OQ-*` is resolved, implement the owner module, not the historical discussion.
- If no suitable `OQ-*` exists, report the exact proposed `OQ-*` entry instead of modifying PRD files unless the user explicitly asked for PRD maintenance.

Required `OQ-*` fields:

- ID
- Title
- Status
- Owner module
- Related modules
- Type
- Blocking
- Problem
- Options, if gameplay-impacting
- Recommended option, if known
- Decision, when resolved
- Implementation impact
- Test impact

## Resolved fixes

- Use `FIX-*` only for resolved contradictions or corrections.
- Every resolved correction must use stable IDs like `FIX-001`; do not reuse deleted IDs.
- Every `FIX-*` must identify one owner module.
- Accepted `FIX-*` entries explain why a correction was made; the corrected owner PRD is the final executable specification.
- If an accepted `FIX-*` and its owner PRD still conflict, stop and report PRD drift.

Required `FIX-*` fields:

- ID
- Title
- Status
- Owner module
- Related modules
- Problem
- Accepted correction
- Gameplay impact
- Implementation impact
- Test impact

## Owner PRD before implementation

- Newly resolved behavior must be documented in the owner PRD before implementation.
- Do not update owner PRDs unless the user explicitly requested PRD maintenance or approved the proposed `OQ-*` / `FIX-*` decision.
- If a decision affects schema, API, constants, IDs, tests, architecture, or MVP scope, update the corresponding owner files in the same documentation change.
- If a change affects MVP scope, update `01_PRODUCT_OVERVIEW.md` and `19_IMPLEMENTATION_ORDER.md`.
- If a change affects LLM development workflow, update `20_LLM_AGENT_RULES.md`.
- Add or update tests after resolution, not before inventing behavior.
- Synchronize static scans and required tests when documentation rules change.

## Language and style

- Preserve the language style of the edited document.
- Do not mix languages within the same requirement, table, or entry unless the user explicitly asks.
- Keep documentation focused and concrete.
- Do not rewrite the entire PRD or reorder large sections unless explicitly requested.
- Avoid large copied fragments from other docs; summarize and link to the owner source.

## Forbidden behavior

- Do not rewrite the entire PRD for a local documentation change.
- Do not duplicate owner tables, schemas, balance values, APIs, payloads, event contracts, or formulas across files.
- Do not create a second source of truth.
- Do not leave `TODO`, `TBD`, `FIXME`, or `???` without an `OQ-*` ID.
- Do not use roadmap, skills, comments, generated docs, or future code as higher authority than owner PRDs.
- Do not resolve PRD-vs-PRD conflicts by preference; stop and report the conflict.
- Do not silently change gameplay requirements in docs without updating owner PRD, `OQ-*`/`FIX-*` when needed, and tests.
- Do not mix languages without explicit request.

## Required checks

When touching documentation or documentation-enforcing tests, verify:

- The requirement has one owner PRD.
- Cross-references point to owner files instead of copied duplicate rules.
- `OQ-*` and `FIX-*` IDs are unique and have required fields.
- No untracked `TODO`, `TBD`, `FIXME`, or `???` remains.
- Resolved fixes reference owner modules.
- Owner PRD, schema/API/constants, and tests are synchronized when behavior changes.
- Static scan expectations in `21_OPEN_QUESTIONS_AND_FIXES.md` remain enforceable.

## Output requirements

When completing documentation/open-question changes, report:

- Owner PRD files changed.
- `OQ-*` / `FIX-*` entries added, changed, or referenced.
- Cross-references added or updated.
- Tests/static scans updated or intentionally not run, with reason.
- Any unresolved ambiguity or PRD drift.
